class Solution {
    public int[] shortestAlternatingPaths(int n, int[][] redEdges, int[][] blueEdges) {
        List<List<Integer>> red = new ArrayList<>();
        List<List<Integer>> blue = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            red.add(new ArrayList<>());
            blue.add(new ArrayList<>());
        }
        for (int[] edge : redEdges) {
            red.get(edge[0]).add(edge[1]);
        }
        for (int[] edge : blueEdges) {
            blue.get(edge[0]).add(edge[1]);
        }
        int[] answer = new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(answer, -1);
        answer[0] = 0;
        Queue<int[]> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        queue.offer(new int[] {0, 0, -1}); // node, distance, color
        boolean[][] visited = new boolean[n][2];
        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            int[] curr = queue.poll();
            int node = curr[0], dist = curr[1], prevColor = curr[2];
            if (visited[node][prevColor == 0 ? 1 : 0]) continue;
            visited[node][prevColor == 0 ? 1 : 0] = true;
            if (answer[node] == -1 || answer[node] > dist) {
                answer[node] = dist;
            }
            List<List<Integer>> nextList = prevColor == 0 ? blue : red;
            int nextColor = prevColor == 0 ? 1 : 0;
            for (int next : nextList.get(node)) {
                if (!visited[next][nextColor]) {
                    queue.offer(new int[] {next, dist + 1, nextColor});
                }
            }
        }
        return answer;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n + m)
space complexity: O(n + m)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses BFS traversal with a queue to efficiently explore the graph in alternating colors, ensuring the shortest path is found. It maintains separate lists for red and blue edges and tracks visited nodes to avoid revisiting them, thus optimizing the search process.
